body: #### section-title ####
content: Operators, Expressions and Statements
----
class: default
----
#### text-block ####
content: An expression is a combination of identifiers, values and operators which computes a value. It is quite similar to an arithmetic expression, with the only difference that the scope of programming languages expressions is way bigger since they can compute any kind of data, be they numerical or otherwise. We have already delved into identifiers and values; what we miss to write proper Python expressions are now the operators. They are special symbols and keywords that instruct a computation between two values. The semantics of an operator depends on the type of its operands.

----
#### section-title ####
content: Logical Operators (Yield Boolean)
----
class: default
----
#### text-block ####
content: Logical operators allow to manipulate and chain boolean values. Non-boolean values can also be operands of a logical operator, but they will be implicitly converted to boolean values with the bool() data type constructor before evaluation.
----
#### image ####
name: not.svg
----
class: small_image
----
#### text-block ####
content: <code class="language-python">not</code> (unary negation) is used to change the state of a boolean type, from <code class="language-python">False</code> to <code class="language-python">True</code>, from <code class="language-python">True</code> to <code class="language-python">False</code>. It is like pressing a switch. "Unary" means that the operator only affects the following operand.
----
#### image ####
name: or.svg
----
class: small_image
----
#### text-block ####
content: <code class="language-python">or</code> is used to build a logical expression that will evaluate <code class="language-python">True</code> if any of the operands is <code class="language-python">True</code>. Look at the diagram on the left: the pipe has a fork with a tap on each side. The fork is the "or" operator, and the taps are the operands; if any of the valves are open (<code class="language-python">True</code>), the water will flow on the other side.
----
#### image ####
name: and.svg
----
class: small_image
----
#### text-block ####
content: <code class="language-python">and</code> (conditional and) is used to build a logical expression that will evaluate <code class="language-python">True</code> if every operand is <code class="language-python">True</code>. Look at the diagram on the left: a straight pipe represents the boolean expression with two taps following each other. The only way to let the water through is to open both valves. Meaning that every operand has to be <code class="language-python">True</code>.

<code class="language-python">and</code> and <code class="language-python">or</code> are also referred to as "short-circuit" operators, because the interpreter will not evaluate the entire expression if unnecessary.
----
