#### text-block ####
content: So, when should you use what? When comparing numbers, text, containers content is good practice to use <code class="language-python">==</code> and <code class="language-python">!=</code>. Avoid <code class="language-python">is</code> and <code class="language-python">is not</code>, they are ambiguous and often not reliable because of caching. Instead, when comparing identifiers to singletons (<code class="language-python">True</code>, <code class="language-python">False</code>, <code class="language-python">None</code>) you should always use <code class="language-python">is</code> and <code class="language-python">is not</code>. Why? Because there is only one instance of each of these type (therefore their identity is reliable) and makes your code more readable.
